<TEXT>
classroom teachers want input on designing 
curriculums selecting principals choosing textbooks and spending 
school funds according to a gallup poll released monday 
teachers overwhelmingly want more say in everything said 
donna rhodes director of the national foundation for the 
improvement of education one of several groups that sponsored the 
study 
the poll found that teachers believe they can make a difference 
in changing overall education policy and reforming the educational 
system on virtually all levels if given the opportunity it was 
released as a gathering of education and business leaders 
recognized 115 elementary and secondary school teachers from 23 
areas 
sixtythree percent of the respondents said they believed they 
could influence change in their own school a great deal 
another 35 percent said a fair amount while 2 percent said 
not very much 
ninetysix percent said the role of teachers should be expanded 
in the area of educational decisionmaking more than nine out of 
10 favored schoolbased decisionmaking which teachers say will 
give them a greater voice in what happens in their classrooms 
the poll found that 86 percent wanted public school teachers to 
have more say in the allocation of funds 78 percent wanted more 
influence over curriculum 56 percent believed they should 
participate in the hiring of other teachers and 69 percent wanted 
input into the selection of the building principal in addition 71 
percent wanted to help choose books and instructional materials 78 
percent wanted a voice in setting teacher and administrative 
salaries and 54 percent wanted a sayso in tenure decisions 
we also want policy makers to come into the classroom said 
roberta e cocking of the los alamos middle school in los alamos 
nm one of the teachers being recognized she said few policy 
makers know much about what goes on daytoday in classrooms 
gallup in may polled 231 semifinalists in this years thanks 
to teachers program the margin of error is plus or minus 6 
percent the program singles out teachers from across the nation 
for recognition it is sponsored by the foundation the national 
alliance of business apple computer inc and group w television 
sales 
rhodes said we believe the polls findings are significant 
because they represent the opinions of some of the best teachers in 
the country educators whose communities view them as the best and 
value what they do said rhodes 
their perception of the condition of education today is 
reflective of that held by the public at large she said 
</TEXT>
