<TEXT>
a man held four 
sheriffs and an interpreter hostage for more than six hours at a 
courthouse monday before an exchange of gunfire that left the 
gunman and three police officers wounded police said 
none of the hostages were hurt and two of the wounded officers 
suffered only superficial injuries in the incident in this 
vancouver suburb said police cpl casey dehaas 
all four wounded were taken to a hospital there was no 
immediate word on the seriousness of the wounds suffered by the 
gunman or the third officer 
police identified the hostagetaker as a 38yearold man who had 
gone to court to appeal a threemonth sentence for violating crab 
fishing regulations and a threemonth sentence for obstructing 
justice 
the man had been free on bail but was taken into custody as a 
condition of bail immediately before his court appearance monday 
dehaas said 
the man took the four provincial sheriffs and an interpreter 
hostage around 10 am pdt in the courthouse lockup 
police cordoned off the area in back of the courthouse and a 
police negotatior talked to the man over the phone members of new 
westminsters emergency response team moved into place 
at 420 pm pdt more than a dozen shots were heard police 
said the shots were confined to the lockup 
seconds after the shots witnesses saw an emergency response 
team member emerge clutching his side the officer collapsed 
police believe the gunman brought a largecaliber handgun to the 
courthouse dehaas said there were no metal detectors at the 
courthouse monday although portable detectors are used for 
highsecurity cases 
