<TEXT>
vladimir zhironovsky chairman of the liberal 
democrats conducts interviews on a park bench not in an office 
his party couldnt afford an office even if one were available 
we dont have any money we dont have any press we dont 
have any advertising he said on the bench in a quiet shady 
corner of sokolniki park in northeast moscow 
nikolai travkin a plainspoken former communist party member 
who is forming a populist movement incites disgruntled citizens to 
throw out his former comrades the russian social democrats are 
looking for coalition partners and communists need not apply 
dozens of parties have formed since the communists and the 
national legislature agreed in february to end the partys monopoly 
on power the political spectrum ranges from monarchist to 
anarchist but the communist party remains dominant 
communist reformer vyacheslav n shostakovsky said the newcomers 
present a sideshow of protoparties while a struggle for 
control goes on in the 19million member organization that has 
ruled the soviet union since 1917 
travkin agrees what counts is not the number of parties but 
their ability to mount a nationwide challenge to the communists 
you can create as many parties as you want but the communist 
party will strangle them like chickens he told supporters at a 
rally 
in pressing for an end to the constitutional monopoly of power 
president mikhail s gorbachev said the communists would struggle 
for the status of the ruling party rather than having it 
guaranteed 
whatever the theory the party still controls newspapers radio 
and television 
it has lost none of the vast staff and organizational experience 
built up over 70 years and party cells in factories ministries 
the military and kgb secret police have not been eliminated 
opponents of the communists have none of those advantages but 
also lack the partys big disadvantage a legacy of repression and 
mismanagement that is an easy target to attack 
oleg rumyantsev said his social democrats are morally and 
politically opposed to the ideology and practical ways of 
revolutionary communism epitomized by the bolsheviks the party 
will consider a coalition with anyone except the communists he 
told the interfax news service 
zhironovsky of the liberal democrats is a lawyer and proponent 
of free markets who has spent years on the edge of the dissident 
movement 
he believes the soviet communists are going the way of eastern 
europes failed regimes 
the question is how they are going to leave and when he 
said 
many prominent people criticize the communist party but forcing 
it out will not be easy 
no big names have joined the small opposition groups telephones 
and apartments are so scarce there is no place for zhironovsky to 
put the liberal democrat headquarters so he splits it between his 
apartment and his office at a publishing house 
he hopes that in the interests of political stability the 
communists will decide to hand over some of their plentiful office 
space without a regular headquarters he said it is impossible 
for his 9000member group to maintain regular contacts even with 
legislators 
lawmakers have a mass of other problems and theyre going to 
spend two or three days looking for me he asked 
the communist reformer shostakovsky said small parties do not 
yet pose a serious challenge and the main contest is between 
reformers and conservatives within the communist party 
there are monarchists in the party as strange as it seems 
and there are anarchists said shostakovsky rector of moscows 
higher party school he is a leader of democratic platform 
reformers who want the party leadership to abandon the idea of 
leading and organizing the entire society 
other members include boris n yeltsin just elected president 
of the russian federation historian yuri afanasiev and gavriil 
popov mayor of moscow 
some kind of party split is almost certain a struggle now is 
under way for control of the party center and with it the majority 
of members 
shostakovsky fears an attempt to seize control by party 
hardliners who accused gorbachevs economic advisers in documents 
published may 13 of intending to dismantle soviet socialism they 
condemned private enterprise legalization of accumulating 
capital thirst for profit and individualism 
a national party central committee document criticized 
democratic platform this spring for threatening to split the party 
if it cannot force reform the differences probably will come to a 
head at the 28th party congress beginning july 2 and it is not 
certain what direction gorbachev will take 
shostakovsky said he did not expect gorbachev to propose great 
changes if none occurred he said democratic platform would leave 
and take 500000 to 600000 supporters along 
it would be the largest opposition group by far but still a 
dwarf beside the mother party 
despite the prominence of many of its members democratic 
platform would face many of the difficulties confronted by other 
opposition groups most of its supporters are intellectuals and 
highly skilled workers and shostakovsky acknowledged it had 
virtually no support in the countryside 
democratic platform probably would cooperate with gorbachev as 
much as possible playing the role of a loyal opposition rather 
than trying to take power away from him 
travkin whose populist message has found an audience with 
radical workers has been a member of democratic platform and still 
has a partnership relationship with it shostakovsky said 
he added however that travkin was pressing too hard there 
is a taste of confrontation about it extremely tough 
confrontation he said 
as for travkin he said his populist democratic party of russia 
wants to replace local communist leaders not engage in endless 
round tables to negotiate issues 
shostakovsky said opponents may be surprised by the communists 
staying power 
they have watched sovietinspired parties in eastern europe 
quickly reduced to demoralized minority parties he said but 
communism was imposed there and was homegrown in the soviet union 
