the 128yearold wreckage of the civil war 
ironclad monitor is fragile but still intact the government said 
as it cleared the way for photographers to venture to the ships 
atlantic grave 
for the first time in 11 years the national oceanic and 
atmospheric administration is permitting research dives to the 
ship which sank in a gale 16 miles off cape hatteras nc in 
1862 
armed with a noaa permit photographer and author rod farb of 
cedar grove nc arrived at the site with a film crew last week 
beating out a scubadiving rival 
farb and gary gentile of philadelphia had vied to become the 
first to dive to the ship since french explorer jacques cousteau 
did it in 1979 
gentile still plans to dive to the ship in several weeks but it 
wont be the same said his attorney peter hess 
do you remember the second guy to cross the atlantic he 
said 
gentile had filed 11 permit applications and written more than 
50 letters to noaa since 1984 seeking permission to photograph the 
wreck he won his monitor permit first but decided to wait until 
the weather improved at the end of june to make the trip hess said 
cousteaus expedition was hampered by bad weather and poor 
visibility and little or no usable footage was produced 
but noaa said farb was blessed with good conditions when he and 
his crew made their first dive at the end of last week noaa part 
of the commerce department is responsible for safeguarding the 
wreckage 
accompanied by a noaa representative farb was expected to 
remain at the site for several days and the agency said it did not 
expect him to release any footage right away 
noaa refused to allow monitor dives after cousteaus trip 
saying the 220foot depth posed a serious and unreasonable risk 
that its own divers would not take 
meanwhile some private divers fearing the wreck was in danger 
of collapse lobbied the agency to permit dives before the 
historic ship was lost 
noaa reversed its position after one of its administrative law 
judges ruled last november that the agency exaggerated safety 
concerns and that a significant number of trained scuba divers 
frequently descend 220 feet 
before permitting farbs dive noaa researchers disclosed friday 
that they descended to the wreck in a submarine on june 12 to make 
a visual record to ensure that artifacts are not tampered with 
later 
the best word to describe the condition is that we believe 
its stable said tim keeney noaa director of ocean and coastal 
resources certainly the hull of the vessel is not made of thick 
metal and there are parts that have caved in however there is 
armor plating surrounding the vessel and that is almost totally 
intact on the port side 
the ships gun turret looks like its in pretty good shape 
keeney said 
the monitor sank after a celebrated battle with the confederate 
ship merrimack in 1862 it was discovered by researchers in 1973 
the merrimack renamed the virginia was destroyed by its crew to 
keep it from being captured by the union 
the monitor appears fragile said irv garrison a noaa marine 
archaeologist who was on the submarine 
time is one thing he said but shes also right in the 
area of a shipping lane and every destroyer that went by may have 
dropped a load on her she might have been depthcharged which 
would be a ironic fate for an old civil war boat 
</TEXT>
