<TEXT>
the renamed communists held a commanding 
lead today in bulgarias first free elections in 58 years bucking 
the anticommunist trend in countries that emerged from the soviet 
orbit in the past year 
the party and once moscows most loyal follower appeared 
likely to become the only ruling party in eastern europe to retain 
power in multiparty elections according to projections from 
independent polling organizations 
however opposition leaders charged that sundays parliamentary 
vote had been marred by irregularities and more than 2000 
protesters demonstrated outside parliament today shouting 
fraud and calling for a general strike 
police cordoned off the building and the crowd appeared to be 
growing the opposition scheduled a mass evening rally for downtown 
sofia 
independent projections gave the socialists heirs to the 
longruling communists about 48 percent of the vote in sundays 
parliamentary vote the main opposition coalition the union of 
democratic forces had just under 35 percent official results were 
expected later today 
there were complaints from opposition officials that the 
ballotcounting was moving very slowly but union chairman zhelyu 
zhelev told reporters that he did not believe the opposition would 
challenge the elections validity 
in the worst case we shall want new elections in districts 
where there have been real flagrant violations he said 
the west german polling organization infas said the opposition 
won the capital of sofia where it was expected to receive about 55 
percent of the vote against 38 percent for the socialists who 
called themselves communist until april 
however the union lagged behind in the countryside where 
analysts had expected the opposition to have a tough time for many 
people outside sofia radical change is feared and the socialists 
represent stability 
the socialists favor introducing economic reforms gradually 
avoiding the shock therapy that has caused steep price rises 
and widespread unemployment in poland 
the 16party union of democratic forces favors a swift move to a 
market economy and restoring private ownership its supporters say 
it offers the best guarantee of democratic change 
the socialists have said they want to govern in a coalition with 
the opposition in order to get a broadbased consensus for tackling 
the countrys economic problems union leaders have ruled out such 
a coalition 
at least 84 percent of the countrys 64 million eligible voters 
cast ballots for the 400seat grand national assembly the central 
election commission said late sunday 
in all 3143 candidates from 38 parties ran for election to the 
parliament half of the seats will be awarded on the basis of 
proportional representation the others allocated according to 
results in 200 districts races runoffs are to be held sunday where 
no candidate wins a majority 
bulgaria is the fifth eastern european country to hold free 
parliamentary elections this year the communists suffered 
resounding defeats in east germany hungary and czechoslovakia in 
romaia the national salvation front a coalition dominated by 
former communists that took power after the overthrow and execution 
of dictator nicolae ceausescu won multiparty elections 
in bulgaria reform communists engineered the nations drive to 
democracy removing longtime hardline communist leader todor 
zhivkov in november 
president petar mladenov has won public support for initiating 
reforms that included a renunciation of the partys monopoly on 
power 
the bulgarian communist party also has deep roots in the 
country the party was founded in 1891 predating the soviet 
communist party 
it captured 20 percent of the vote in 1932 the countrys last 
free elections and has ruled bulgaria since 1944 
opposition leaders charged that a socialist victory would stem 
from the continuing strong influence through patronage of the 
communist nomenklatura or apparatus 
but political observers said the union lost potential supporters 
because of poor leadership 
the association for free and fair elections a bulgarian 
monitoring group said its vote projections gave the socialists 
483 percent of the vote against 349 percent for the union and 83 
percent for the agrarian party formerly a docile ally of the 
communists infas had similar projections 
the only other party projected to win seats was the movement for 
rights and freedoms which was receiving about 80 percent of the 
vote in areas heavily populated by the 15 million ethnic turkish 
minority bta reported 
the projections gave the ethnic turkish group from 57 to 84 
percent of the vote nationwide 
thousands of bulgarian and foreign observers monitored the 
voting there were only scattered reports of irregularities 
including allegations of stolen ballot papers and lastminute 
campaigning banned under election law 
opposition campaign manager petko simeonov told a news 
conference today that the union believed the elections to have been 
fair in most places however he said he gave election officials a 
list of 211 cases of alleged violations 
simeonov said conditions for free elections had been secured in 
most places but there has been strong moral pressure on the 
electorate especially in small villages 
he claimed that after the voting signals of different 
violations of election procedure came like a tidal wave 
beforehand actor and opposition activist yosif serchadzhiev 
alleging electoral fraud in the village of pazardzhik during an 
appearance on live national televison burst into tears and ran off 
camera 
heated onair exchanges and shouting followed 
the main task of the new parliament will be to write a new 
consititution to usher in democratic and economic reforms the 
parliament must also deal with a 10 billion foreign debt growing 
inflation and shortages of basic consumer items including sugar and 
cheese 
