renamed the elbert parr tuttle us court of appeals building today 
after its oldest living judge 
last christmas an 11th circuit judge was killed by a mail bomb 
and a similar bomb was safely intercepted at the courthouse 
another bomb killed a savannah lawyer and one was sent to the naacp 
office in jacksonville fla 
but the ceremony for tuttle was expected to recall an earlier 
era when the court was the target of death threats and political 
pressure because of landmark civil rights rulings 
tuttle was appointed by president eisenhower in 1954 three 
months after the supreme courts brown vs board of education 
ruling struck down school desegregation 
he became a leader of the old 5th us circuit court of appeals 
now the 11th when it served as the legal battleground for the 
civil rights movement 
as chief judge from 1961 to 1967 tuttle helped decide landmark 
cases involving jim crow laws voting rights jury discrimination 
employment discrimination reapportionment and school 
desegregation including the order to admit james meredith to the 
university of mississippi 
in a dissenting opinion later adopted by the us supreme 
court he argued in 1966 that georgias house of representatives 
could not refuse to seat julian bond for opposing the vietnam war 
tuttle took senior or semiretired status in 1968 
raised in california and hawaii tuttle came to atlanta in 1923 
and with his brotherinlaw founded a law firm that took on 
controversial cases 
it battled to win a new trial for a black man convicted of 
raping a white woman and challenged a georgia law under which a 
black communist was sentenced to 20 years on a chain gang for 
distributing communist party literature 
he became a state republican leader in the 1940s after becoming 
appalled at the whitesonly policies of georgias democratic party 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

