<TEXT>
the supreme court refused today to limit the 
power of a federal judges appointees to supervise elections and 
other activities of the teamsters union 
the justices without comment rejected arguments that lower 
courts were unlawfully enforcing orders aimed at ridding the union 
of corruption and ties to organized crime 
the case stems from the federal governments 1988 lawsuit 
accusing the teamsters of violating the racketeer influenced and 
corrupt organizations act 
the union agreed on the eve of a trial to settle the suit under 
a consent decree approved by us district judge david edelstein in 
new york city 
the judge appointed three officials to discipline corrupt union 
leaders to help run the union and to supervise its future 
elections 
the union then challenged the power of one appointee to monitor 
local balloting leading up to next years election of international 
teamsters officers 
the teamsters also said edelstein violated members freespeech 
rights by ordering the union to distribute monthly reports issued 
by the courtappointed administrator 
the judge said the union could comply either by continuing 
monthly publication of its magazine the international teamster or 
by mailing the administrators report separately 
the order was prompted by the unions decision to scale back the 
magazine publishing it quarterly rather than monthly 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals without holding a 
hearing rejected the unions appeal of edelsteins orders 
in the appeal acted on today union lawyers said the appeals 
court illegally refused to review edelsteins orders 
the case is teamsters vs us 891602 
