the supreme court today made it easier for 
federal judges to penalize lawyers who file lawsuits determined to 
be improper or frivolous 
the court voting 81 ruled against cooter amp gell a 
washington dc law firm penalized 21402 for filing an 
antitrust suit based on research deemed inadequate 
the justices said a judge had authority to impose the fine even 
though the law firm agreed to drop the suit 
cooter amp gell represented dashs designer a now bankrupt 
discount mens clothing store 
dashs filed an antitrust suit against hartmarx corp 
manufacturers and distributors of hickeyfreeman and hart 
schaffner amp marx mens clothing 
dashs said hartmarx illegally sold the brands exclusively to 
only one retailer in each of various major cities nationwide 
cooter amp gell relied in part on research by a secretary at the 
law firm who telephoned some retailers in washington and three 
other cities to determine whether hartmarx had such an exclusivity 
policy 
hartmarx later asked for dismissal of the cooter amp gell suit 
after submitting affidavits that showed it distributed to as many 
as 20 different retailers in some markets 
the law firm agreed to drop the suit 
the us circuit court of appeals here upheld the 21402 
penalty against cooter amp gell last year the appeals court invoked 
a rule against frivolous suits noting that cooter amp gells claims 
were not supported by the skimpy research it performed 
justice sandra day oconnor writing for the high court today 
said the law firms withdrawal of the suit did not divest the 
federal courts of power to impose such sanctions 
justice john paul stevens dissented he said the ruling 
undermines another rule encouraging the withdrawal of groundless 
suits 
the high court today overturned part of the appeals court ruling 
that would have cost cooter amp gell more money oconnor said 
hartmarx is not entitled to be reimbursed for legal fees it 
incurred in fighting appeals brought by cooter amp gell 
the case is cooter amp gell vs hartmarx 89275 
