<TEXT>
the transalaska oil pipeline will be 
shut down for about 12 hours tuesday to replace corroded lines at 
several pump stations officials said 
the lines could begin leaking if left unrepaired said marnie 
isaacs spokeswoman for the alyeska pipeline service co 
the affected steel pipes are not buried and are smaller than the 
48inch diameter line that links prudhoe bay with the marine 
terminal at valdez about 800 miles to the south she said 
the corrosion apparently was caused by bacteria in water mixed 
with the north slope crude oil she said sea water is injected 
into oil fields to increase pressure making it easier to recover 
the oil 
weve noticed it in numerous places in several pump 
stations she said theres a very very small percentage of 
water thats in the oil and that starts a corrosion process 
the corrosion has occurred mostly at the northernmost pump 
stations and is worst at pump station no 1 at prudhoe bay she 
said 
its not a threat to the line right now but internal 
corrosion is a more rapid form of corrosion than weve seen along 
the mainline pipe its something we do need to address ms 
isaacs said if left unrepaired there would be a danger of 
leakage 
alyeska which operates the pipeline for a consortium of seven 
oil companies has said it plans to spend some 800 million to 
repair external corrosion on the main line during the next five 
years state officials have said that repair costs could top 1 
billion 
alyeska will continue to receive about 20000 barrels of oil per 
hour during the shutdown compared with the standard 73000 
barrelperhouraverage the oil will be held in two tanks that 
have a combined capacity of about 350000 barrels 
because of the shutdown about 636000 fewer barrels of oil will 
flow through the line tuesday than normal 
