<TEXT>
john m poindexter was sentenced today to six 
months in prison for lying to congress to conceal key details of 
the irancontra affair when he was president reagans national 
security adviser 
poindexter showed no emotion as he stood before the judge for 
sentencing saying only your honor i dont have any comment 
he then became the first irancontra defendant sentenced to prison 
us district judge harold h greene told the retired navy 
admiral that imprisonment was necessary to deter other public 
officials from lying while conducting governmental business 
greene said that a sentence without incarceration would be 
tantamount to a statement that to lie to and to obstruct congress 
was of no great moment 
admiral poindexter and his associates obstructed the congress 
nullifying the decisions that body had made by cutting off 
direct military aid to nicaraguan contras greene said 
greene did not impose a fine and said poindexter could remain 
free while he appealed the five felony convictions of making false 
statements to congress and obstructing the inquiries of lawmakers 
into the irancontra affair 
but the judge made it clear that he felt that poindexters 
crimes were serious rejecting a defense argument that the retired 
navy officerss 33 years of service to the government should weigh 
against incarceration 
with all due respect ot the distinguished military records of 
admiral poindexter and other irancontra defendants they had 
no standing in a democratic society to ignore the decisions of 
elected officials 
greene noted that under federal sentencing guidelines which do 
not affect this case because they took effect after the irancontra 
affair poindexter would have been sentenced to 21 months to 27 
months for the five felonies 
but the judge said that he would not force poindexter 53 to 
serve such a lengthy sentence while six other irancontra 
codefendants had received terms of probation 
he also noted that poindexter conducted his defense in a 
responsible but not a dishonest or disruptive manner an apparent 
reference to norths trial tactics two years ago 
without naming north greene said that unlike other 
defendants poindexter did not take the stand to exculpate himself 
by lying under oath 
the comment was an obvious reference to testimony by north the 
only irancontra defendant to testify on his own behalf 
poindexter was convicted april 7 of conspiracy two counts of 
making false statements and two counts of obstructing congressional 
inquiries 
while poindexters lawyers argued that he had suffered enough 
and should not be sent to prison chief prosecutor lawrence e 
walsh argued that poindexters role as a topranking official was 
different from those of the other irancontra defendants including 
north 
the judge said that after the irancontra affair unraveled 
poindexter and north engaged in the destruction of evidence one 
step ahead of the congress and two steps ahead of the attorney 
general and the fbi 
prosecutor dan k webb told greene that he had no doubt that 
poindexter was a decent honorable man who had served his country 
as a naval officer and adviser to reagan but webb said that 
poindexters crime was not an isolated incident 
he called it a prolonged and protracted course of conduct to 
obstruct congress 
he said that the irancontra affair is a classic example of 
what happens when these laws are violated 
we literally had this admiral and one very misguided and 
confused lieutenant colonel operating a private war in nicaragua 
and congress didnt know about it webb said referring to the 
secret efforts to arm the contras after congress shut off aid 
defense lawyer richard beckler urged greene to spare poindexter 
a prison term citing his accomplishments as a career naval officer 
beckler said that when he served as reagans national security 
adviser i dont think anyone can appreciate the power and 
pressure that bore on him 
every step can be a misstep clearly missteps were taken 
here beckler said 
but both greene and the prosecutor noted that poindexter had 
shown no remorse or acceptance of his guilt while pleading for 
leniency 
poindexter served as reagans national security adviser from 
late 1985 until the revelations about the irancontra affair forced 
his resignation in november 1986 
a jury found poindexter guilty of making false statements to 
congress by denying in a letter that north and others were secretly 
helping the contras 
he was also convicted of making false statements and altering or 
destroying documents to conceal white house knowledge of an israeli 
shipment of hawk antiaircraft missiles to iran in 1985 
prosecutors contended that poindexter denied that he knew 
anything about the shipment until january 1986 to conceal a 
politically embarrassing memo signed by reagan that linked the 
weapons sales to the release of american hostages in lebanon 
subsequent intelligence findings signed by reagan to 
authorize other weapons sales said the purpose of the deals was to 
establish contact with political moderates in iran as well as seek 
release of hostages 
as details of usiran arms shipments unfolded in the fall of 
1986 reagan denied that he ever engaged in a pure trade of arms 
for hostages he said the initiative also was undertaken to make 
contact with political moderates in iran 
also convicted of irancontra crimes were arms dealers albert 
hakim and richard v secord conservative fundraisers richard 
miller and the late carl r spitz channell and former national 
security adviser robert mcfarlane 
