<TEXT>
while americans overwhelmingly voice support for 
a constitutional ban on flag burning researchers say that view is 
based more on emotion than on any analysis of freespeech issues 
from reciting the pledge of allegiance to singing the national 
anthem at ballgames rituals celebrating the flag are so ingrained 
in american society they raise it to the level of an icon social 
researchers said 
its a value thats been engendered since childhood from cub 
scouts to the fourth of july parade said tom smith general 
social survey director at the national opinion research center in 
chicago this is deeply rooted 
as such americans who are asked their view on flagburning are 
unlikely to mull the freespeech issues that come before the us 
supreme court said smith instead what we see is a lot of 
visceral reaction to it 
that reaction showed up strongly in surveys after the supreme 
court first ruled last summer that flag burning is a form of free 
speech seven in 10 respondents and more in some polls opposed 
the ruling 
nearly as many roughly twothirds in several surveys said they 
favored a constitutional amendment to ban flag burning that issue 
is likely to resurface now that the court reaffirmed its ruling 
monday 
smith said those opinions are unlikely to change over time 
because they are based on deepseated values rather than current 
events this is a deep symbolic attachment he said these 
kinds of opinions go back to childhood and socialization they are 
very hard to sway 
but howard schuman director of the survey research center at 
the university of michigan said opinions on such matters can 
change quickly precisely because they are questioned so rarely 
a sociologist has coined the phrase cultural cliche its 
like you should brush your teeth twice a day and you should pay 
respect to the flag said schuman there are a series of things 
like this that one learns at a very young age and are rarely 
questioned 
however he said in some cases where they do get questioned 
people quickly change because theyve never thought about it 
before everybody can switch easily when they have good reason 
to 
smith noted that warnings about the potential freespeech 
repercussions of a constitutional ban are not widely known and 
could raise opposition once they are circulated polls have not yet 
probed that possibility he said 
if a poll strongly laid out the freespeech issues before asking 
opinions on flag burning some respondents may be less apt to 
support a ban for example smith said polls find opposition to 
taxes in general but support for taxes earmarked for a positive 
purpose such as cleaning the environment 
there are certain things that to most americans sound so 
objectionable on their face that you have to explain either the 
rationale or the counterargument smith said if you just 
mention flag burning youre going to get a majority of people 
objecting youd get a lot closer to a 5050 split if you 
emphasized free speech as a part of american life 
</TEXT>
