the 80 million insat satellite will replace one that was 
deployed in 1983 by the crew of the shuttle challenger it will be 
boosted into a stationary orbit 22300 miles high about 10 days 
after liftoff said sastri vasantha project director of indias 
department of space 
once it becomes operational in midjuly the satellite will 
provide a telecommunications link in india it also will send video 
and voice signals to television radio and disaster warning 
receivers and send weather observations to a forecasting center in 
new delhi for distribution across india 
the satellite originally was scheduled to ride a delta rocket 
into orbit last june but was damaged in a launch pad accident a 
week before liftoff a cable on a crane broke and dropped a heavy 
hook on the satellite 
ford aerospace which built the satellite returned the 
spacecraft to palo alto calif workers there replaced an antenna 
and made other repairs costing 10 million said fred stang 
director of business development for the company 
the earthquake that struck northern california in october caused 
further damage about a dozen cells in the satellites solar 
panels had to be replaced the cost for that was about 150000 
stang said 
ford aerospace has insured the satellite for any problems while 
it is on the ground the indian government which also has 
insurance assumes responsibility after liftoff 
because of the year delay india has had to lease the services 
of other satellite communications companies vasantha said the 
insat satellite that will be replaced is operating at about 70 
percent capacity he said 
the new spacecraft is the fourth and final in a series of 
indias insat 1 satellites it has a working lifetime of seven 
years an updated version the insat 2 will be carried into space 
next year by europes ariane rocket 
it is the fourth commercial launch of mcdonnell douglas delta 
rocket the rocket and launch services for tuesdays launch cost 
nearly 50 million 
