<TEXT>
wideranging oilspill prevention and 
cleanup legislation was signed into law monday by gov bob 
martinez as a crippled norwegian oil tanker continued to blaze 
across the gulf of mexico 
the legislation introduced in the wake of last years 
catastrophic exxon valdez spill in alaska increases companies 
financial liability for oil spills and increases safety and 
training requirements for ships and terminals 
so much of floridas appeal rests with its unique coastline 
and we simply cant afford to risk a repeat of the tragic alaska 
oil spill here martinez said 
the governor also noted the ongoing battle to contain the 
disaster in the gulf of mexico 57 miles southeast of galveston 
texas where a supertanker carrying 38 million gallons of oil was 
set ablaze and crippled by an explosion saturday 
these are real problems that do occur martinez said to 
our knowledge theres not another state in the union that has a 
bill of this comprehensive nature dealing with oil spills 
i believe that others will begin to follow suit for the same 
reasons we did they have coastlines to protect and the only way 
to protect is to be able to immediately respond he said 
the legislation which is a compromise with oil shippers and 
retailers requires vessels and terminals to produce detailed 
spillresponse plans and terminals to buy equipment to quickly 
contain a spill 
only certified pilots or deputy pilots will be allowed to move 
large ships in florida waters which extend 3 miles into the 
atlantic ocean and 10 miles into the gulf which is shallower 
closer to shore 
fines of up to 25000 could be assessed for violations 
where oil and other potential pollutants are loaded and unloaded 
in large quantities terminal operators will have to use booms to 
seal off surrounding waters to contain any spills 
liability limits for spill damage and cleanup costs for 
transporters and cargo owners jump to 50 million from 14 million 
the state would have to go to court to collect any of that money 
in addition if future oil drilling is approved off floridas 
coast the cap on a state fund to pay for spill cleanups would 
double to 100 million using an existing 2centsabarrel excise 
tax on oil and other potential pollutants 
if a major spill depletes the fund now at 32 million the 
governor and cabinet could increase the tax to 10 cents until the 
fund is replenished 
environmentalists generally praised the law as a positive first 
step in protecting the state from oil spills but said more must be 
done 
in particular the financial limits on cleanup liability for oil 
companies and shippers should be removed said ann whitfield of the 
florida public interest research group citing the 2 billion cost 
of the valdez spill 
this is a dramatic improvement but it still maintains the 
principle that the oil industry should be protected from cleanup 
costs whitfield said if they were not protected it would be 
a financial incentive for them to have the safety equipment to do 
the job 
although the law is likely to raise oil companies costs of 
doing business in florida martinez cited the size of the states 
market 
you have no costs if you do it right the governor added 
the cost only comes if you dont take the proper precautions 
