<TEXT>
americans are becoming more concerned that 
businesses and the government are invading their privacy by asking 
too many questions and sharing the information with others a poll 
released monday said 
seventyone percent of those surveyed by louis harris amp 
associates believe consumers have lost all control over how 
companies use information about them and circulate it to other 
firms the poll said 
the poll was commissioned by equifax an atlantabased 
corporation that provides clients with credit insurance and 
marketing information about potential customers 
the poll said that 79 percent of the public is either very 
concerned or somewhat concerned about threats to their personal 
privacy compared with 77 percent in a 1983 harris survey and 64 
percent in 1978 in 1970 only 34 percent said they were concerned 
about privacy issues 
thirty percent said they had decided against applying for a job 
credit or insurance because they didnt want to provide certain 
kinds of information about themselves the survey said 
but 78 percent said they would be upset if they couldnt get 
credit based on their record of paying bills the survey said 
humphrey taylor president of louis harris said the poll sends 
a warning to private business adding it would be a serious 
mistake for business to ignore the high and growing levels of 
concern that we are reporting today 
most americans are willing to give personal information when 
they believe it will be used in ways they consider proper such as 
employers checking whether a job applicant has a criminal record 
and credit card companies checking a persons credit history the 
poll said 
eightythree percent of the respondents said employers should be 
allowed to require drug tests for job applicants 
sixtynine percent said phone companies should be allowed to 
offer caller id which displays the phone number of an incoming 
call if customers can block their number from being shown 
the random telephone poll included 2254 interviews in january 
and february and an additional 2253 interviews in april with 
about half of the first group of people being reinterviewed the 
margin of error was plus or minus 2 percent 
