<TEXT>
the united states and mexico took a first step 
monday toward negotiating a free trade pact that a white house 
official said could one day lead to a single north american market 
president bush and mexican president carlos salinas de gortari 
agreed at a private dinner sunday night to have their trade 
officials begin preparations for the formal talks bush spokesman 
marlin fitzwater said 
the presidents agreed that the greatest possible mutual 
benefit would derive from an agreement that entails gradual and 
comprehensive elimination of trade barriers fitzwater said 
he said preparatory work by us trade representative carla 
hills and jaime puche mexicos minister of commerce and industrial 
development would be done between now and december when the two 
presidents will meet again 
that session is tentatively scheduled for monterrey mexico 
salinas told us business leaders that the most important 
immediate result of a usmexican freetrade agreement will be 
to increase trade and investment flows between both nations 
we need our exports to have stable secure access to the us 
market he said in remarks prepared for delivery to the business 
round table in exchange salinas said mexico will provide new 
markets for us goods and new investment opportunities for 
american businesses 
mexico does not want to be late for the worlds appointment 
with the 21st century salinas added 
the two countries will seek a pact that will improve and 
expand the flow of goods services and investment between the 
united states and mexico fitzwater said 
he said changes in immigration and emigration laws were not 
envisioned 
the united states signed a freetrade pact with canada in 1988 
under which all tariffs and other trade barriers are being 
eliminated by the year 2000 
in his 1988 campaign bush proposed a single north american 
trade zone a unified market of 335 million people without 
trade barriers 
bush still advocates such an approach and it is anticipated 
that would be an end result of a trade agreement with mexico 
fitzwater said however he noted a separate freetrade pact would 
also have to be struck between mexico and canada 
bush called canadian prime minister brian mulroney on sunday 
night to tell him of the developments fitzwater said mulroney 
