james a baker iii and members of congress he was to meet on 
tuesday with vice president dan quayle 
although the united states has pressed for free trade between 
the two nations salinas a harvardeducated economist initially 
was cool to the idea however more recently he has suggested that 
an economic recovery in mexico will not be possible without it 
his change of heart occurred after mexican efforts to seek 
foreign investment from europe fell far short of expectations 
mexico is the united states third largest trading partner after 
canada and japan with twoway trade of 52 billion last year 
the united states shipped 2497 billion worth of exports into 
mexico in 1989 and imported 2719 billion in mexican goods for a 
us trade deficit with mexico of 22 billion 
winning congressional agreement on an elimination of all trade 
barriers with mexico could prove more difficult than getting 
passage of the canadian pact 
the aflcio has voiced skepticism about such an arrangement 
suggesting that a freetrade pact could cost jobs in the united 
states once tariffs were removed on mexican products made by 
lowpaid mexican workers 
the jobs issue is a difficult one fitzwater said its 
one both sides are aware of we want an agreement that is 
beneficial to both sides both in terms of investment as well as 
jobs and labor markets 
salinas in his speech called unfounded concerns by us 
labor of job losses 
to assume that the creation of new jobs in mexico will be 
attained at the expense of the american worker is to ignore 
mexicos enormous potential as a market for united states exports 
and the complementarity of our economies he said 
</TEXT>
