<TEXT>
about 60000 supporters of the opposition 
alliance took to the streets monday to protest the projected 
victory of the socialist party heir to the communists who have 
controlled the balkan nation since 1944 
crowds rallied outside election headquarters shouting down 
with the red mafia after unofficial returns from sundays 
parliamentary vote showed the 16party union of democratic forces 
in second place 
hundreds of cars and taxis most of them displaying udf flags 
later crisscrossed downtown sofia honking their horns passersby 
cheered and waved udf flags 
small groups of udf supporters walked through the city shouting 
anticommunist slogans or cheering the alliance 
the opposition alliance had predicted victory in the nations 
first free balloting in 58 years and its leaders claimed election 
irregularities affected the outcome of voting for the 400 
parliamentary seats 
official election results were not expected until tuesday 
if their victory is confirmed the socialists would be the only 
ruling party in eastern europe to be returned to power in a 
multiparty election the communists changed their name to 
socialists in april 
the party has said it would proceedly slowly with reforms the 
opposition alliance favors swift change to a westernstyle market 
economy to tackle growing inflation a 10 billion foreign debt and 
consumer shortages 
plamen darakchiev an alliance member and deputy editor in chief 
of the partys daily demokratsiya predicted the new political 
lineup will leave our people polarized in parliament 
opposition chairman zhelyu zhelev told the rally the group would 
not form a coalition with the ruling party 
in the national assembly we will be a powerful opposition 
faction he said 
in a nationwide television broadcast premier andrei lukanov 
urged all public and political forces to work together the 
state news agency bta reported 
there are no losers in the present elections because in the 
final reckoning the victory of democracy is a victory for all 
he was quoted as saying 
only in sofia the capital did the alliance top the socialists 
according to a forecast by the west german polling group infas the 
socialists took the countryside and smaller cities 
the infas projections showed the socialists with 47 percent of 
the vote the opposition alliance with 36 percent and the 
mainstream agrarian party once a docile communist ally with 8 
percent 
according to infas the mainly ethnic turkish movement for 
rights and freedoms will get 57 percent and the remaining 38 
parties the rest 
the projections were based on the vote in 250 polling districts 
of the 400 parliament seats 200 will be allocated according to 
the percentage of votes each party receives the remainder will go 
to candidates who receive more than 50 percent of the vote 
a second round of voting is scheduled for sunday for races in 
which no candidate received more than 50 percent of the vote 
western observers said the voting was generally free and fair 
although there were scattered incidents of apparent manipulation 
michel aliotmarie who headed the european democratic union 
delegation said any irregularities did not appear to have affected 
the results substantially the state bta news agency reported 
georgi spasov spokesman for the opposition coalition said 
alleged irregularities included illegal campaigning in front of 
polling stations 
we are not trying to reject totally the results but we will 
call the attention of the central electoral committee and we shall 
seek reelection in some places said petar beron an opposition 
official 
aliotmarie attributed the socialists lead to the partys 
predominance in public life and the early scheduling of the 
elections 
the opposition wanted the elections postponed until fall to 
allow more time for parties to organize 
the communist party in bulgaria has been a strong political 
force for nearly a century it won 20 percent of the vote in the 
last free election in 1932 and has ruled since 1944 
bulgaria had only a nascent opposition when reform communists 
including current president petar mladenov ousted longtime 
communist strongman todor zhivkov last november 
the opposition alliance has gained considerable support in 
recent months especially in sofia as it pressed the communists to 
accelerate change 
