<TEXT>
prime minister brian mulroney said monday that 
canada should proceed with the ratification by june 23 of the meech 
lake constitutional accord despite some provinces fears about the 
special status afforded quebec 
it is clear there are serious misunderstandings in this 
country we cannot afford to ignore he told the house of commons 
in his first speech since the 11 first ministers mulroney and 
the 10 provincial premiers reached a tentative deal over the 
weekend to ratify the controversial accord 
under the deal holdout provinces newfoundland manitoba and new 
brunswick will try to pass meech lake before june 23 when by law 
it is due to expire under meech lake quebec a largely 
frenchspeaking province with 67 million of canadas 25 million 
population would be recognized as a distinct society other 
amendments include broadening the powers of all provinces senate 
reform and a canada clause regarding aboriginals 
after seven rancorous days of private talks convened at the 
behest of mulroney the ministers came up with a package of 
agreements that would allow the accord to be approved 
premier clyde wells of newfoundland said monday his legislature 
will hold a free vote on the accord with deputies voting their 
conscience and not by party dictates he said he would have 
preferred a full referendum of his provinces 550000plus 
residents 
wells believes meech lake injures the tradition of equality 
among provinces and weakens the federal state 
a legislative vote was seen as good news for meech lake 
supporters because it would be faster than a referendum and would 
hold more potential for approval than a referendum 
manitoba and new brunswick legislatures are expected to approve 
meech lake premiers robert bourassa of quebec and david peterson 
of ontario on monday publicly opposed extending the june 23 
deadline monday helping to scuttle any referendum plans by wells 
as being too timeconsuming 
the 3yearold accord would make quebec a full supporter of the 
1982 constitution which the province refused to sign because it 
failed to distinguish quebec as a distinct society 
</TEXT>
