<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ordered the department 
of energy to pay 250000 to the state of ohio and the us 
treasury in a case involving a troubled nuclear weapons plant 
the 6th us circuit court of appeals upheld a district court 
ruling that the resource conservation and recovery act and the 
clean air act dont shield the doe from liability because congress 
waived sovereign immunity for civil actions under both statutes 
the energy department owns the feed materials production center 
18 miles northwest of cincinnati which was used from 1952 until 
last year to process uranium for nuclear weapons the plant has 
been idle since last year to allow cleanup of the site 
area residents already have won a 78 million settlement from 
the doe for their claim that their health may be endangered and 
their property value diminished because of their closeness to the 
site 
the state of ohio sued the energy department in 1986 requesting 
fines for improper hazardous waste disposal and release of 
radioactive materials at the plant 
us district court in cincinnati never got to address whether 
the energy department and its contractors should be liable for 
improperly disposing hazardous waste or polluting the air or water 
the parties in the case agreed in december 1988 to a settlement 
in which doe would pay up to 1 million of that amount 750000 
was to be paid to ohio with 250000 riding on the appeal of the 
sovereign immunity issue 
under mondays ruling the doe will have to pay the remaining 
250000 of the settlement half to ohio and half to the federal 
treasury 
hazardous wastes dating from the world war ii manhattan project 
are stored at fernald a citizen watchdog group says many barrels 
storing hazardous and chemical wastes are rusting and leaking 
the us environmental protection agency is supervising the 
cleanup of the site which is expected to take up to 50 years 
judge boyce f martin jr wrote the opinion of the court in 
which judge nathaniel r jones concurred judge ralph b guy jr 
wrote a dissenting opinion 
ohio attorney general anthony celebrezze jr called mondays 
ruling another victory for ohio and its citizens in what has 
often been a complex and frustrating battle with the us 
department of energy and the federal department of justice 
calls to the doe seeking comment were not returned 
</TEXT>
