<TEXT>
candy on the cob thats the trend 
nowadays in garden corn but not everybody thrills to supersweet 
some preferring the oldtime flavor 
the raccoon isnt fussy unless you put up foolproof defenses 
hell get your best ears whether standard varieties like silver 
queen or the new saccharine entries with names like kandy 
korn how sweet it is xtra sweet and florida 
staysweet 
in this sugary scene breeders aimed at developing types of corn 
that stay sweet after picking 
as everyone knows standard corn turns to starch quickly hence 
the ritual of rushing freshpicked ears to the alreadyboiling pot 
before the sweetness fades the new varieties however can lie 
around as long as two weeks after harvesting and remain sweet a 
boon to agribusiness the supermarket road stands and perhaps the 
dentists office 
liking to try new things ive grown the ultrasweety but 
missed what my palate remebered as true corn flavor the ears 
tasted more like dessert than a vegetable course numerous such 
reactions from home gardeners have prompted the national gardening 
association to recommend that you try a few for taste before 
discarding old favorites 
fortunately most seed houses still carry silver queen a 
latematuring white variety that many of us regard as the best of 
the kind that you rush to the pot 
another oldtime star golden cross bantam is not so easy 
