photo of two ears of a sugarextender called breeders 
choice said to stay sweet and tender on the stalk for at least 
10 days 
youve got to look sharply when ordering from a catalog for 
warnings that some supersweets need isolation from your standard 
corn otherwise crosspollination will produce tough starchy 
kernels of both types on the plus side some of the new ones are 
smaller no taller than 4 or 5 feet a welcome development for 
gardeners with limited space 
whether we opt now for extrasweet or standard corn takes a 
gardener centuries back to americas indian origins we celebrate 
the legacy with succotash the hearty corn and beans dish created 
long before nutritionists talked of balancing carbohydrates and 
proteins 
you plant corn in springtime when as they say young oak leaves 
are about as large as a mouses ears and start harvetsing in the 
full heat of the summer if youre a beginner be sure to plant at 
least two rows but preferably a block of four to insure good 
pollination without it the ears will turn out woefully short of 
kernels 
the old saying that you should grow enough corn for both you and 
the raccoon may be all right if you plant an acre but a gardener 
hoping for maybe 50 ears in a season may find his whole crop 
devoured by nightstriking masked bandits many gardeners 
unwilling to undertake the work and expense of securing the crop 
just give up on corn after such tragedies 
but ive fought back and can say with fingers crossed that 
ive frustrated the raccoon for several years now i credit mainly 
a batteryoperated hot wire that i strung atop my preexisting 
chicken wire fence 
the wire long used in livestock control delivers a harmless 
but memorable shock on contact and the raccoon thinks it over 
before trying again 
such fencers as they are called are available from garden 
supply companies hardware stores or horse equipment places i got 
mine from sears and did the job for a total of about 100 
living in the country at a distance from neighbors ive also 
installed in the garden a blinking light and a radio tuned to an 
allnight news station these are aimed at frightening deer as well 
as raccoons 
baiting the hot wire with strips of aluminum coated with 
peanut butter gives an inquisitive deer a jolt on the snout and it 
will stay away after that 
thats the theory anyhow and for me it beats going to 
barbershops for scraps of human hair another supposed deer 
deterrent i also have an enthusiastic helper a young shelty named 
lucy with fast feet and a sharp bark 
