donald trump has reached a tentative debt 
restructuring agreement with his bank creditors that would provide 
him with both money and time to mend his troubled empire a source 
familiar with the deal confirmed today 
the source who asked to remain anonymous said the banks agreed 
over the weekend to lend trump an additional 60 million and to 
suspend interest payments on 2 billion in debt 
in exchange trump would pledge some of the remaining real 
estate or casino assets that arent completely collateralized 
including the trump plaza hotel in atlantic city nj and the 
trump tower building in manhattan the source said 
norma foerderer an executive assistant for trump said the 
trump organization would have no comment on the report of an 
agreemnt which first appeared in todays wall street journal we 
have nothing to say about it she said 
trump confirmed last week that he was negotiating with major 
banks to restructure his debt the banks reportedly have become 
concerned that trump may not be able to handle the billiondollar 
debt he ran up buying big real estate and casino properties given 
the current slowdowns in both industries 
recent purchases such as the plaza hotel and trump shuttle 
airline have added to trumps financial woes because neither is 
reported to be making money 
trumps biggest bank creditors including citicorp chase 
manhattan corp bankers trust new york corp and manufacturers 
hanvover corp planned to discuss the weekend debt restructuring 
deal today with about 10 smaller creditors according to the source 
if any one of the other banks do not go along then the deal 
does not work the journal quoted on unidentified banker as 
saying 
bankers trust spokesman thomas parisi said he couldnt comment 
on the reported deal adding when an agreement is reached well 
probably release a statement 
other banks contacted had no immediate comment 
the source familiar with the negotiations said the major banks 
contributions toward the 60 million will be porportionate to the 
amount they previously lent with citicorp and bankers trust making 
up around twothirds of the new loan 
