foxboro co a leading maker of systems that 
control manufacturing processes said monday it is exploring what 
it called an alliance with other firms that could involve the 
sale of the company 
the announcement came amid speculation that began last week 
about a possible takeover of the company the talk drove up the 
price of foxboro stock which closed monsday at 30 a share up 
150 on the new york stock exchange 
a week ago the stock sold for 24 a share last year it traded 
as low as 1862 said albert turner a securities analyst at duff 
amp phelps in chicago 
foxboro systems are used to record and control processes in 
manufacturing such as temperature pressure humidity and liquid 
levels its customers are largely in the chemical and petroleum 
industries and include such familiar names as exxon corp and dow 
chemical co 
the international company based in the suburb of foxboro 
employs 7000 people the company reported a net loss for 1989 of 
46 million or 37 cents a share on sales of 598 million 
in a carefully worded announcement the company said it was 
exploring alternatives with respect to a possible strategic 
alliance with a limited number of firms 
such an alliance it said could add complementary strengths 
to the companys existing strong process control capability 
the deal it is exploring the company added could involve an 
equity investment in all or a substantial portion of its stock 
it also said however that no decision had been made on whether 
such a deal might even transpire 
telephone calls to john c fuller a member of the foxboro board 
and a vice president for investor relations were not returned 
foxboro would be an attractive buy turner said among its 
attributes are an old and loyal customer base and a new product 
line first offered two years ago that enables foxboro systems to be 
integrated with those of other companies 
but the new system has had costly bugs in it turner said 
its not clear that all of the problems have been completely 
worked out in this new system and this company has had to borrow 
money to finance its operations in the last four years turner 
said they could use a little financial backing 
robert sullivan an analyst at painewebber inc in new york 
said foxboro is coming out of a restructuring period 
the companys record in the last few years has been quite 
erratic which has led to some dissatisfaction on the part of some 
stockholders sullivan said 
its a big and growing market and as manufacturing companies 
are forced by law to reduce pollution one of the things they will 
be forced to spend money on is equipment to reduce pollution 
sullivan said 
