the trust created in manville corps bankruptcy 
to compensate victims of asbestosrelated diseases said monday it 
is exploring alternatives to ease a cash shortage that could delay 
some payments until the 21st century 
john c sawhill chairman of the manville personal injury 
settlement trust issued a statement that the trust wants to 
quickly resolve the current legal issues and return its attention 
to settling claims 
the statement did not specify alternatives being examined by the 
trust 
the trust said it has in the past rejected moneyraising methods 
including insurancetype deferred settlements investment and asset 
management options sale of part of its manville stock and 
borrowing money 
on friday a federal bankruptcy judge appointed new york 
attorney leon silverman one of the architects of manvilles 
reoganization plan to find ways of restructuring the 25 billion 
trust 
earlier this month a federal judge and a new york state judge 
ordered the bankruptcy court to overhaul the trust one change 
would be in a widely criticized payment method that compensates 
most claimants on the basis of when their lawsuit is filed 
the trust was criticized because of a cash shortage induced by 
more cases larger payouts and quicker settlements than expected 
it has said some claimants filing this year will not get paid until 
the year 2025 
the trust was formed as a separate legal entity in manvilles 
1988 reorganization six years after the denver company was driven 
into bankruptcy court by lawsuits over production of asbestos its 
main asset is ownership of a majority of manville stock 
the parties are talking about what can be done in this 
situation said theodore kleinman the trusts chief financial 
officer every possible alternative will be visited in the course 
of that exploration were very anxious to try to do whats right 
here 
manville was the nations largest maker of asbestos the 
insulation and building material found to cause severe and 
sometimes fatal illnesses manville to date has settled more than 
22000 claims by victims but still has more than 130000 pending 
in the statement the trust said it has received 958 million 
from manville and its insurers to date it said it has paid out 
739 million 638 million of that directly to claimants 
of some 219 million in cash on hand as of march 30 113 
million already is committed to paying claims over the next year 
the rest of the money is designated for prior settlement claims 
legal expenses and operations costs 
the trust has said it will have no new income until manville 
makes its first annual 75 million payment to the trust next year 
